Text:
Mundane and Annerose face each other in the arena,
the referee standing between them.
(His secret is his overwhelming speed.)
(Moreover, he has yet to show his limits.)

Mundane has won all of his previous matches without
any real fighting. And why is that? Because none of
his foes have been able to keep up with him. That
has to be part of it.

(But...he wields his blade like an apprentice, and
his posture is all over the place.)

Anyone properly trained in the blade would
never have such terrible posture.

What if Mundane doesn't like to actually cross blades
with his foes?

What if he's afraid that in doing so, it would put
his shoddy skills on display?

In short, he has found a way to win without engaging
his opponents in order to keep his flaw hidden. Thus
it should be possible to best him so long as one is
not dazzled by his speed.
This is the conclusion Annerose reaches.

If there is one thing that worries her...it is the
weights Mundane has removed.

If, now that he is unburdened, Mundane can move at
velocities faster than she can react to...
Even Annerose might very well lose.
(In which case...)
Annerose Nichtsehen versus...
Mundane Mann!
Ready? Begin!

Annerose dashes in close to Mundane as soon as the
match starts.

(If I can restrain his movement, he won't be able to
beat me!)
Haaaaaah!!!

Before anyone can blink, Annerose gets in close and
swings her sword at Mundane with a roar.

It is an attack that would have caught anyone
completely off guard...
Except that he blocks it.
(He's quick, all right.)

Under normal circumstances, no one could have
repelled such a slash in time, but Mundane has
gone and done just that.
Hyaaaaah!!!
Her blade flies toward her now-still foe once more.

(If I can keep him too busy to use his speed, then
sooner or later...)
She hammers at his defenses three, four, five times...
At last, his balance slips.
I win!

Sure of her victory, she aims a slash straight at
Mundane's chest.
Her blade finds its mark...or does it?
Huh?

There is no resistance to her sword. On the contrary,
Mundane has instantly vanished from her field of
vision.
That was my afterimage.

Annerose's shoulders tremble as she hears his voice
from behind her.
Annerose slowly turns around.

"I must not let him see that I'm shaken," she tells
herself.
Right behind her stands Mundane.
(What do I do?)
He can move much more swiftly than she can react.
The next thing she knows, Mundane is gone.
He moved before she could even think.

It wasn't skill or experience that enables her to
respond to the faint vibration in the air she felt
just then—it is merely luck.
A tremendous impact sends Annerose reeling.
Ngh...!
She lets out a gasp of pain.
He's so much faster...
than I imagined...!
Have to stop this...
Agh...!

If there was magic in his attacks, I'd already be
dead.
...I admit it.
You are strong. Absurdly so.

She can see Mundane now, standing there with his
sword dangling from his hand, not poised to fight,
not pressing the attack.

Annerose doesn't see this as arrogance, mainly because
Mundane really is that good.
(He has me beat in both speed and power...)
(So I only have one option left...)

Annerose calms her ragged breathing and readies
herself.
The aristocrats are also watching with bated breath.
Stop moving...
...And try for a counter.
Yes, I do believe that is her only hope.

Odds are low, but it can't be completely ruled out.
If she can catch up to his speed...

The moment Mundane strikes is Annerose's final
chance at victory. But there is a problem—can she
actually pull it off?

If your reflexes aren't fast enough, use your
experience instead. Not enough experience?
Then gut feeling will do. Use any means
necessary.

If she can just get the timing right...then all she
needs to do is cut him down with all of her
hard-earned finesse.

Annerose waits for the instant to arrive, quiet yet
also focused to the core.

There is no advance warning whatsoever—Mundane was
there, and then he wasn't.
Now!

Though it is only empty space at present, she aims
her slash to her right, diagonally behind her as soon
as Mundane vanishes.
The next moment...
Mundane appears, and Annerose knows she has won.
You're mine!

Her blade is placed directly in his path, and at
his speed there is no way he can avoid it.
Or so she thought.
Huh...?
Mundane stops.

He stops just out of Annerose's reach as if he had
been planning to do so all along.

Her sword slices the air, grazing the bridge of his
nose.
This was not coincidence—he gauged the space exactly.

I thought I was matching his movements, but he was
the one matching mine!
What terrifying foresight.

Annerose assumed she had read his attack and adapted
to it, but that was not the case at all.
No, it was the exact opposite.
(What perfect spacing.)

It all became clear to Annerose then. Mundane Mann...
possesses superlative skill.

Now she stands hopeless as he moves to deliver the
fatal blow.
It is the slowest movement he had made that day.

However...it is also the pinnacle of prowess,
so perfect that it could be art.
Ahh...
(It's so beautiful.)
That was her last thought before she blacked out.
